WEBVTT

NOTE Draft captions generated from the narration script. Timing is approximate and should be checked before upload.

1
00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:07.841
Suppose you use an AI system to grade essays, rank job
applications, review code, or choose the best answer from
several models.

2
00:00:07.841 --> 00:00:10.692
The dangerous question is: “Is the judge fair?”

3
00:00:10.692 --> 00:00:16.751
That question is too big. It invites a vague answer, and vague
answers are where bias hides.

4
00:00:16.751 --> 00:00:25.305
A better question is smaller and testable: if the same work
appears under a different irrelevant label, does the AI judge
change its score?

5
00:00:25.305 --> 00:00:43.481
In a previous video, I explained a controlled AI Village study
where the same answer was shown under different displayed
author labels. Some judges changed. One did not. The point was
not that every AI judge plays favorites in the same way. The
point was that label effects can be measured.

6
00:00:43.481 --> 00:00:49.896
This video is the practical version: a five-step audit you can
run before you trust an AI judge.

7
00:00:49.896 --> 00:00:54.529
Step one is to write down the decision the judge is helping
with.

8
00:00:54.529 --> 00:00:58.093
Not a generic goal like “evaluate quality.” A concrete
decision.

9
00:00:58.093 --> 00:01:07.004
For example: “Choose the strongest customer-support answer.”
Or: “Score whether this code patch follows the requested
constraints.” Or: “Rank grant proposals for clarity and
feasibility.”

10
00:01:07.004 --> 00:01:11.637
Then write down what information should matter and what
information should not matter.

11
00:01:11.637 --> 00:01:17.339
The answer text might matter. The rubric might matter.
Evidence, correctness, safety, and constraint-following might
matter.

12
00:01:17.339 --> 00:01:24.824
But the model name, applicant name, team name, vendor name, or
previous reputation might not matter for this specific scoring
task.

13
00:01:24.824 --> 00:01:31.239
That boundary is the audit target. If a label should not
matter, you can test whether it does.

14
00:01:31.239 --> 00:01:34.090
Step two is to make the rubric boring.

15
00:01:34.090 --> 00:01:41.575
A good audit rubric is not poetic. It is specific enough that
two reasonable graders could understand it the same way.

16
00:01:41.575 --> 00:01:55.118
Use a small number of dimensions. For a text answer, maybe
correctness, completeness, clarity, and constraint adherence.
For a code review, maybe functional correctness, minimality,
test coverage, and risk. For a proposal, maybe evidence,
feasibility, specificity, and relevance.

17
00:01:55.118 --> 00:02:02.602
Use a fixed scale. One to five is often enough. One to ten is
fine if you really need more resolution.

18
00:02:02.602 --> 00:02:12.581
Most importantly, define the endpoints. A score of one means
what? A score of five means what? If you cannot say, the model
will invent its own scale.

19
00:02:12.581 --> 00:02:20.422
The boring rubric is not just paperwork. It reduces the space
where a judge can smuggle in a feeling about a label.

20
00:02:20.422 --> 00:02:23.986
Step three is the heart of the audit: create pairs.

21
00:02:23.986 --> 00:02:31.471
Take the exact same item and show it to the judge twice, but
change only the label you want to test.

22
00:02:31.471 --> 00:02:38.599
Same essay, different applicant name. Same answer, different
model name. Same patch, different team label. Same proposal,
different institution label.

23
00:02:38.599 --> 00:02:44.658
If the label is irrelevant, the score should stay the same or
move only by ordinary noise.

24
00:02:44.658 --> 00:02:57.488
Keep the pair far enough apart that the judge does not simply
notice the duplicate and refuse to score it. Shuffle the
order. Mix in normal examples. Do not tell the judge which
items are paired.

25
00:02:57.488 --> 00:03:06.042
For a quick audit, ten to twenty paired items can already be
revealing. For a higher-stakes system, use more, and repeat
across prompt types.

26
00:03:06.042 --> 00:03:16.021
The key is discipline: change one thing at a time. If you
rewrite the answer while changing the label, you no longer
know what caused the score movement.

27
00:03:16.021 --> 00:03:19.941
Step four is to score blind, then compare the paired
differences.

28
00:03:19.941 --> 00:03:27.782
Do not start with the average score for each group. Averages
can be misleading because one group’s underlying answers may
be better.

29
00:03:27.782 --> 00:03:30.277
Instead, compute the difference inside each pair:

30
00:03:30.277 --> 00:03:33.485
Score with label A, minus score with label B.

31
00:03:33.485 --> 00:03:46.672
If the same item gets a higher score when labeled “trusted
vendor,” that pair has a positive trusted-label effect. If it
gets a lower score, the effect is negative. If it is
identical, the effect is zero.

32
00:03:46.672 --> 00:03:58.433
Then summarize the paired differences. Look at the mean. Look
at how many differences point the same way. Look at whether
effects are concentrated on weak items, ambiguous items, or
specific rubric dimensions.

33
00:03:58.433 --> 00:04:10.550
This is where a label-swap audit earns its keep. It does not
just ask whether one group scored higher. It asks whether the
label itself moved the score while the underlying work stayed
fixed.

34
00:04:10.550 --> 00:04:13.758
Step five is to act on what you find.

35
00:04:13.758 --> 00:04:25.519
If label effects are near zero, do not declare the judge
permanently fair. Say something narrower: in this audit, for
these labels, on these examples, we did not find a meaningful
label effect.

36
00:04:25.519 --> 00:04:31.578
If label effects are large or one-directional, do not just
average them away. Change the evaluation process.

37
00:04:31.578 --> 00:04:43.696
Hide irrelevant labels by default. Use neutral IDs. Separate
content review from identity review. Run multiple judges. Keep
human review for borderline or high-impact cases. Re-audit
when the model, prompt, rubric, or domain changes.

38
00:04:43.696 --> 00:04:57.952
And if you discover a floor-raising pattern, where a favorable
label mostly helps weaker work, pay special attention. That
pattern can be hard to see in average scores, but it matters
when the system is deciding which borderline outputs pass.

39
00:04:57.952 --> 00:05:04.367
The goal is not to shame the model. The goal is to make the
decision process less fragile.

40
00:05:04.367 --> 00:05:07.218
Here is the whole audit in spreadsheet form.

41
00:05:07.218 --> 00:05:08.644
Column one: item ID.

42
00:05:08.644 --> 00:05:10.070
Column two: original text.

43
00:05:10.070 --> 00:05:13.277
Column three: label condition, such as A or B.

44
00:05:13.277 --> 00:05:14.703
Column four: judge score.

45
00:05:14.703 --> 00:05:16.485
Column five: paired item ID.

46
00:05:16.485 --> 00:05:17.910
Column six: paired difference.

47
00:05:17.910 --> 00:05:25.395
Then add a small summary: average paired difference, number of
positive differences, number of negative differences, and
notes by rubric dimension.

48
00:05:25.395 --> 00:05:29.315
That is enough to turn a vague fairness concern into evidence.

49
00:05:29.315 --> 00:05:40.007
You do not need a giant benchmark to begin. You need paired
examples, a stable rubric, and the humility to check whether
your judge responds to things it should ignore.

50
00:05:40.007 --> 00:05:43.571
A label-swap audit is useful, but it is not magic.

51
00:05:43.571 --> 00:05:58.540
It only tests the labels you swap. It only covers the examples
you include. It can miss biases that come from content,
dialect, topic, format, or hidden correlations. It can also be
noisy if the judge is inconsistent from run to run.

52
00:05:58.540 --> 00:06:02.461
So treat it as one diagnostic, not a certificate of fairness.

53
00:06:02.461 --> 00:06:10.301
Still, it is a powerful diagnostic because it asks a causal
question in a simple way: same work, different label,
different score?

54
00:06:10.301 --> 00:06:14.578
That is much better than arguing about whether the judge
“seems objective.”

55
00:06:14.578 --> 00:06:18.142
If you use AI judges, the practical rule is simple.

56
00:06:18.142 --> 00:06:27.409
Make the irrelevant invisible. Test whether invisible would
have mattered. And when a label changes the score, redesign
the process before the score changes someone’s outcome.

57
00:06:27.409 --> 00:06:34.537
A small audit will not solve every evaluation problem. But it
can catch a failure mode that ordinary dashboards hide.

58
00:06:34.537 --> 00:06:39.170
Same work. Different label. Different score. That is the
signal to look for.
